# Agent Instructions — LLM Red Teaming Framework

## Project purpose
Automated adversarial testing of LLM applications.
Sends attack prompts to a target model and evaluates responses for safety failures.
Built as a portfolio project for BlueDot Impact Technical AI Safety Sprint.

## Stack
- Python 3.11+
- OpenAI API (target model)
- SQLite (results storage, WAL mode)
- FastAPI (results API)
- Streamlit (dashboard)
- uv (package management)

## Build order
config/.env → target.py → prompts/ → evaluator.py → database.py → run_eval.py → api.py → dashboard.py

## File roles
- target.py       — sends prompts to the LLM, returns response string
- evaluator.py    — takes (response, category), returns {passed, reason}
- database.py     — SQLite init, save, fetch functions
- run_eval.py     — CLI runner, wires everything together, writes JSONL output
- api.py          — FastAPI endpoints to query results
- dashboard.py    — Streamlit visualisation of results

## Coding conventions
- Keep functions small — one job per function
- Add a one-line comment above each function explaining what it does
- No unnecessary abstractions — if it's only used once, keep it inline
- No external libraries unless already in pyproject.toml
- Use argparse for CLI args (not click or typer)
- All results go in experiments/YYMMDD_<model>/results.jsonl

## Known limitations (do not try to fix without user direction)
- Hallucination detection is heuristic-only — keyword rules cannot reliably detect it
- Evaluator returns passed=None for ambiguous responses — this is intentional
- Single-turn attacks only — multi-turn is Phase 2
- Results do not transfer across models — always test each model separately

## Setup
uv sync
cp .env.example .env  # add your OPENAI_API_KEY
python run_eval.py --target gpt-3.5-turbo
